    <statement><p>Add or subtract the rational expressions to a single rational expression and then simplify. If applicable, state the restricted domain.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{{\frac{1}{r+6}+\frac{6}{r-6}} =}</m> <fillin characters="40" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\frac{7r+30}{\left(r+6\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-6\right)}, \left(-\infty ,\infty \right)</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   {\frac{1}{r+6}+\frac{6}{r-6}} 
      \amp = {\frac{1}{r+6}} \cdot \frac{(r - 6)}{(r - 6)} +\frac{6}{r - 6} \cdot \frac{(r+6)}{(r+6)}  \\
      \amp = {\frac{r-6+6\mathopen{}\left(r+6\right)}{\left(r+6\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-6\right)}} \\
      \amp = {\frac{r-6+6r+36}{\left(r+6\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-6\right)}} \\
      \amp = {\frac{7r+30}{\left(r+6\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-6\right)}}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
</solution>
